These are some of the safest remakes I've ever seen and for that reason I think they fit their purpose reasonably well imo.

There ya go, my two cents on the matter ✌

All in all I don't think these games are the best but I also don't think they're the worst. This is a better way of reintroducing pokemon to newer gens and giving kids a chance to play these games without parents breaking their wallets to get them.

Anyway, I just feel like so much more could have been done with it and they just played it extremely safe. But at the same time it's mostly optional so not a huge deal. Also it taking up a corner of the screen was a bit off putting tbh.
The addition of HMs being on the poketch is great but it's not really necessary. We could have just had an explanation about helping pokemon like before and moved on but 🤷‍♂️

And finally, the last thing that kinda bugged me was the poketch. I know that it's intended purpose back in the day was to be multifunctional and help you with various tasks throughout the game (hence having a calculator for Fantina's gym)
And lets not even get into the fact most of the ones you get through exploring and beating gyms are absolute shit. I feel for people who are trying to breed for egg moves because y i k e s
Third, the scarcity of TMS was low key annoying. I guess I've been spoiled recently with how some tms are breakable and others aren't but having all of the tms be breakable was a let down tbh.

Second, the bike controls are absolutely shit in this game. I barely ever used my bike because it was so difficult to control even on the low speed setting. Dunno what the hell happened there but it was a big 😬 for me.
I'm not a competitive battler anymore (haven't been since ORAS) and those fights genuinely felt like Battle Tower moments- which isn't a bad thing but for me it was very frustrating.

Especially when you consider that for 90% of the game, I was one shotting just about everything with type advantage.

It took me 4 solid tries to get through the Elite 4 and Cynthia and I only barely made it through by the skin of my teeth

First of all, the Elite 4 is literally on crack. Sure it was hard back in DPP but my GOD did we really need to have two trainers with recover stall??? I get wanting it to be challenging but... not like that.
Now lets get into what I didn't like about the game and some of you may have seen these takes from others but 🤷‍♂️

I didn't have a strong opinion one or the other about the art style but it has grown on me a little. I think they wanted to recapture the feeling of older games while also making it feel more modern and this was a pretty okay choice imo. Not great, but okay.

I also lowkey appreciate that there wasn't a huge level spike like in the originals when you go to get your 8th gym badge. But in hindsight, this kinda screwed me over towards end game- which we'll get into here shortly.

I liked the changes made to the Underground so that it had more purpose than just a silly little mini game at best. I actually did some level grinding for the Elite 4 down there and that was super helpful considering I don't use the VS Seeker all that much 🤷‍♂️
The game was honestly pretty fun and chill- a bit easier than expected but that's just how pokemon games have been recently. It was a nice little nostalgia trip for me if nothing else.

Overall, things are not great but I don't think it's the end of the world. I can only hope that the devs listen to the community and address these issues as quickly as possible because if not, we may see a lot of players go elsewhere. And that sucks.

I also like the inclusion of character portraits in the HUD- although it would be nice if they could match it to cosmetics but I understand that that's a pain in the ass to do given the customization options in the game.

I like the hook counter in the HUD. It's extremely helpful for both sides as you'll be able to tell who is more likely to do what. It also lets killers know when they're tunneling- if they choose to care that is.

The attention to detail in both the new maps is phenomenal. Meat Plant doesn't feel like a slog to go through as much because it feels like you can actually breathe in it without getting sniffed out too soon.
Now that's all the negatives I can pull from this update at face value BUT here are some good things I took from this.

Fourth: New Maps

Honestly, my only gripe is with the Asylum map. It feels entirely too open and entirely too bright. It's not entirely terrible but I have seen reports of entire tiles being bugged so... yeah. Not a good look there.

Third: New Survivor Animations

I'mma be honest with y'all and say I don't really mind these new animations. Yes they're a little weird but like most things, we can get used to them. Moving on.

I can understand latency issues and things of that nature are almost entirely out of their hands- however, this just seems ridiculous. Perhaps it's the new animations, maybe it's the hit registration being fucked all together, point is it's bad.

Second: Hitboxes

I don't know how they managed to make hitboxes worse but they certainly are. I'm getting hits through pallets way more often than I should as killer and I'm getting hit from Coup De Grace range without killers having the perk.

I played quite a bit of both killer and survivor and the fact that I couldn't tell you how many gens had been done and what other players were doing half of the time says a lot.

Maybe if things were all on the left side of the screen it wouldn't be as bad but this is just bad.
Let's get the obvious out of the way- the HUD. It's absolutely atrocious. I mean no disrespect to devs but fact of the matter is things are way too scattered on the screen and it makes zero sense.

School can be great for networking and building a good foundation for you to stand on, but it's not the only way you can do it. There's nothing wrong with taking time and doing what you want. Believe that.
So I'm standing my ground on this one. I hope that anyone questioning going to school who sees this thinks about what's important to them and understands it before making any rash decisions.

I was miserable in school and I am working to unlearn a lot bad mindsets it has taught me over the years. This will take time, and whether or not I feel comfy going back is my decision and mine alone.

I catch a lot of shit for this decision and am constantly being pressured to doubt myself and reconsider but at the end of the day, I get one life. One life to with as I please and I want to enjoy it as much as I can.

I don't know that I will finish my degree or attempt to go back and do something else. Right now my priority is getting myself in order and doing what makes me feel good about myself and my work. Plain and simple.

If you ask me it was a bad idea for me to run to college right away. It did me more harm than good and I recognized that 4 years too late. That's not to say college is bad and no artist should ever do it but for me, it just wasn't the right choice.

Again, not a call out on anyone, but these are things I have thought about since I left and I've come to these conclusions on my own. On top of this, I was never a great student and hated structured education since the beginning.

I did what I could while I was there. I sought therapy, I participated in club activities and organized events but at the end of the day it was really toxic and overall dangerous to my mental health because nothing ever came from those experiences.

I had some decent friends and few decent professors but overall I felt alone and alienated from a lot of the community that I was supposed to be a part of. Even in my art classes it felt that way and I hated it because it felt like everyone hated me for no reason.

3: Bad environment. I won't go into specifics here and this is by no means a call out for my old school but if I've learned anything in my time away from it it's that a good environment does wonders for your mental and physical well being.

And yes I'm fully aware a well rounded education is necessary but I'm not just talking about gen eds here. Even my art classes were lacking in that department too. There was no reason, at least to me, to push myself because I would get nothing out of it besides a piece of paper.

2: Lack of self motivation. A lot of the classes I was taking felt benign and unnecessary and some of them genuinely were unnecessary. I wasn't pushing myself because the classes didn't hold the goals I sought for myself on any level.

Not only that but it seemed like people didn't seem to care if I did well or not. There were very limited resources I could use when things started getting bad and all of those resources ended up falling through on me in the end.
1: Not having the support I needed both and on and off campus. I struggle a lot with depression and anxiety and constantly having people try to convince me to switch majors was a big downer.
